You know what's holding you back.
‚†Ä
It's not your diet.
‚†Ä
You know how to eat to achieve your goals.
‚†Ä
It's not your workouts.
‚†Ä
You know that it's important to stay active.
‚†Ä
It's not a lack of information.
‚†Ä
There's a buttload of information freely available to you.
‚†Ä
(searching for it is probably how you wound up on my page in the first place!)
‚†Ä
What's holding you back from taking action and achieving your goals has nothing to do with fitness.
‚†Ä
It's your work.
It's your family.
It's your mindset.
It's your friendships.
It's your relationships.
‚†Ä
Both the good & the bad.
‚†Ä
When I hop on a call with potential clients, the first questions I ask are:
‚†Ä
"Are you married?"
"Do you have kids?"
"What do you do for a living?"
"What do you do for fun?"
"Are you introverted or extroverted?"
‚†Ä
Questions like those above tell me so much more about that person's struggle with fitness than whatever diet & exercise protocols they've followed in the past ever could.
‚†Ä

‚†Ä
If you can't stay consistent with fitness longer than a few weeks, or you feel like there's nothing that works for you‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
It's because you aren't addressing the real issues in your life.
‚†Ä
So... what's your next step?
‚†Ä
Unfortunately, I can't speak to your situation directly.
‚†Ä
But I can tell you this...
‚†Ä
You are in control of your life.
‚†Ä
Regardless of what problems you currently have‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
You are in control of the action(s) you take to improve them moving forward.
‚†Ä
And fitness can help.
‚†Ä
It can be the start of a positive feedback loop.
‚†Ä
The positive choices you make with your diet & exercise can encourage positive choices in other areas of your life.
‚†Ä
It can give you the strength to speak to your boss about changing an unfair work situation.
‚†Ä
It can give you the courage to finally have that hard conversation with your significant other.
‚†Ä
Fitness can, literally, change your life for the better.
‚†Ä
But only if you use it the right way.
‚†Ä
Fitness isn‚Äôt about ‚Äúfixing‚Äù what‚Äôs ‚Äúbroken‚Ä¶‚Äù
‚†Ä
Fitness is about becoming better, taking back control, and creating the life you know you‚Äôre meant to live.

‚†Ä
Are you REALLY pushing yourself as hard as you think during your workouts?
‚†Ä

‚†Ä

‚†Ä
Wanna be successful?
‚†Ä

Learn to be okay with making mistakes.

Learn to see your mistakes as opportunities to grow and get better.

I‚Äôm not bashing intuitive eating.
‚†Ä
In fact, I agree with almost everything intuitive eating preaches.
‚†Ä
My issue is with the idea that everyone should be able to *intuitively* make the healthiest choices in every situation.
‚†Ä
Let‚Äôs use an example of two different people ‚Äî Jill & Jane
‚†Ä
Jill has been a personal trainer for over ten years. She‚Äôs spent periods of time tracking her food, educating herself, and developing strategies & habits for making healthy food choices.
‚†Ä
Jane has been overweight her entire life, hopping from one FAD diet to next. She hasn‚Äôt spent much of any time tracking or learning about nutrition (outside of the latest trends she‚Äôll see in magazines).
‚†Ä
Do you think Jane is in a place to eating intuitively like Jill?
‚†Ä
Hell no.
‚†Ä
Jane‚Äôs body isn‚Äôt telling her to eat fruits & veggies ‚Äî it‚Äôs telling her to reach for the foods she‚Äôs habitually eaten up to this point. And those food choices weren‚Äôt shaped by her body‚Äôs needs, but rather her lifestyle and environment growing up.
‚†Ä
If Jane tried to hop directly into intuitive eating, there‚Äôs a good chance she‚Äôd feel disappointed in herself ever time she'd fall back into old eating habits.
‚†Ä
~
‚†Ä
Everyone can develop habits & strategies for making healthy choices, but it won‚Äôt come from eating intuitively right off the bat‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
It‚Äôll come from learning to eat mindfully.
‚†Ä
As a mindful eater, you‚Äôre aware of calories, macros, and the importance of eating whole, nutritious foods. You‚Äôre also aware of how your food environment, upbringing, and emotions influence your cravings.
‚†Ä
Time I‚Äôve spent tracking and educating myself is what helps me avoid gaining back the 140 pounds I've lost.
‚†Ä
Intuitively, I want to eat pancakes with extra syrup each morning‚Ä¶ but mindfully, I know I‚Äôll feel better eating eggs, veggies, & fruit. 
Intuitively, I want to polish off an entire pint of Ben & Jerry‚Äôs... but mindfully, I know having something small and getting to bed will help me feel my best physically & mentally the next day.
‚†Ä
Yeah, it‚Äôs *just* terminology‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
But terminology is important ‚Äî especially for someone in a vulnerable state who‚Äôs struggled with fitness their entire life.
‚Äî
‚†Ä

Success with fitness isn‚Äôt about what you‚Äôre going to do in a day, week, month, or year.
‚†Ä
It‚Äôs about what you do in THIS moment.
‚†Ä
Then the next moment...
‚†Ä
And the next...
‚†Ä
It‚Äôs not about a single good or poor choice either.
‚†Ä
You don‚Äôt get fit from one healthy meal or one solid workout ‚Äî just like you don‚Äôt get fat from one unhealthy meal or one skipped workout. ‚†Ä
~
‚†Ä
You've heard this stuff before...
‚†Ä
You and I may not have had the chance to talk directly about your unique struggles, but I would venture to say your struggles aren‚Äôt with figuring out WHAT to do...
‚†Ä
You know you need to be in a deficit.
You know you need to eat healthy
You know you need to exercise.
You know consistency is key.
‚†Ä
Your struggles come from DOING those things consistently ‚Äî especially in the face of temptations.
‚†Ä
Eating healthy is easy-peasy...
‚†Ä
Until you‚Äôre out with your friends on Taco Tuesday. ‚†Ä
Working out isn‚Äôt that big of a deal...
‚†Ä
Until you have a busy, tiring day, and you don‚Äôt want to spend your precious ‚Äúme time‚Äù going to the gym.
‚†Ä
I know this is difficult.
‚†Ä
Especially when you‚Äôre trying to make the right choice in a tempting environment. ‚†Ä
But remember that YOU are in control.
‚†Ä
YOU can (and should) make the choice that is going to make YOU happiest.
‚†Ä
The two questions in the pic above are a great place to start...
‚†Ä
They help to temporarily take you out of the moment so that you can think logically about the choice you‚Äôre about to make.
‚†Ä
Thing is, sometimes going over your targets is worth it...
‚†Ä
[ I‚Äôve had my fair share of high-calorie Taco Tuesdays! üåÆüòãüçπ]
‚†Ä
But most of the time, you‚Äôll find that the short-term satisfaction just isn‚Äôt really worth the negative impact it‚Äôll have towards your long-term goals.
‚†Ä
Especially if your health is a priority.
‚†Ä
The Bottom Line:
‚†Ä
Your success is determined by the collective choices you make in each moment.
‚†Ä
Focus on making the right choices MOST of the time, and you will be successful. More importantly, you‚Äôll be happier knowing that you‚Äôre consistently taking action towards what you want most. üí™
‚†Ä

I started Weight Watchers when I was 13.
‚†Ä
I lost 25 pounds in the first two months!
‚†Ä
After another few months, though, I had fallen off track and gained back those 25 pounds‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
And then some.
‚†Ä
A year later, I tried Weight Watchers again, lost 15-20 quick pounds, and then gained it all back (plus more).
‚†Ä
I repeated this process over and over and over again with different diets until I found myself weighing over 300 pounds!
‚†Ä
It wasn‚Äôt till I learned what I‚Äôm about to tell you that everything changed...
‚†Ä
Every diet you can think of can help you lose weight, and that's because every diet should help you do three things:
‚†Ä
1. Eat more whole foods
2. Eat fewer junk foods
3. Eat fewer calories
‚†Ä
It‚Äôs less about WHY a diet works and more about HOW it works.
‚†Ä
That's what's going to determine your ability to stay consistent long enough to see results.
‚†Ä
For most people, a successful diet comes from avoiding restriction and resistance as possible.
‚†Ä
It's why I'm not a fan of the Keto diet for weight loss.
‚†Ä
Yes, it forces you to eat fewer junk foods, more whole foods, and often fewer calories, but the amount of restriction & resistance it creates makes it nearly impossible to follow long-term.
‚†Ä
Especially for regular people with regular lives.
‚†Ä
If you've been struggling to stay consistent with a specific diet plan, I want you to pay close attention to what I'm about to say‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
Your diet plan should help you eat fewer calories, fewer junk foods, and more whole foods‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
But in a way that fits around your life as much as possible.
‚†Ä
Same thing with exercise.
‚†Ä
The less resistance, the better.
‚†Ä
HOW you set up your diet & exercise plan is so stinkin' important that I created an entire course around it.
‚†Ä
In this course, I talk about six "laws" everyone needs to follow to get the body of their dreams in a way that's effective, sustainable, and flexibly fits around your current lifestyle.
‚†Ä
These laws help me stay lean year round, and I teach them to all of my clients.

I'm not sure I've ever worked with a client that wasn't primarily (or at least partially) motivated by weight loss.
‚†Ä
It's not a bad thing either.
‚†Ä
There's nothing at all wrong with wanting to see the number on the scale go down, especially if you need to lose to get back to a healthy body weight range.
‚†Ä
But if you are going into this ALL-IN on one thing ‚Äî weight loss ‚Äî then you're going to struggle to make a real, lasting change.
‚†Ä
I've seen it happen too many times‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
A client will get a rush of motivation seeing the scale drop quickly at the start, but when things start to (inevitably) slow down, they start falling apart.
‚†Ä
They either a) quit, or b) try to restrict more (which usually ends in quitting).
‚†Ä
This thing they forget is that regardless of how long it takes them to lose weight, they're going to reach a point where they'll be maintaining a lean & healthy body.
‚†Ä
If you're not already thinking about how your diet & exercise changes are going to fit into your life long-term ‚Äî as in... the rest of your life ‚Äî then you're doing yourself a huge disservice.
‚†Ä
Weight loss may be the goal now, but it's not the win.
‚†Ä
The win is wanting to lose weight. (develops ambition)
The win is showing up every day. (develops consistency)
The win is trusting the process. (develops action)
The win is never giving up. (develops grit)
‚†Ä
The win is the PROCESS (journey) ‚Äî not the outcome.
‚†Ä
The physical outcome may be what's motivating you now, but the process of getting there is what'll build the mental toughness that translates into lifelong success.
‚†Ä
So be patience.
‚†Ä
There's no reason to feel rushed.
‚†Ä
I know it's cliche, but you really do have all the time you need to be successful with fitness.
‚†Ä
Takeaways:
‚†Ä
- it's okay to get motivated by weight loss.
- It's not okay to focus solely on weight loss.
- the process is what builds the right mentality.
- the right mentality leads to lifelong success.
‚Äî

For many-a-folk, food cravings are the culprit keeping them from achieving their goals.
‚†Ä
So it's no surprise that one of the most common questions I get asked is, "How do I get rid of cravings once and for all?"
‚†Ä
The truth about food cravings is this...
‚†Ä
They're 100% normal.
‚†Ä
Every single person has cravings that come and go throughout the day‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
The goal isn't to get rid of them but instead learn how to control them.
‚†Ä
And that comes down to one simple things‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
Awareness.
‚†Ä
Struggle to control snacking at work? Stop putting yourself in an environment where you can easily reach for them.
‚†Ä
Can't stop overeating candy at night? Stop buying the jumbo-size packs, or don't buy them at all.
‚†Ä
An approach I see work best for my clients is, simple enough, planning.
‚†Ä
My client Jamie, for example, almost always wants something sweet right after dinner. Instead of restricting herself, she'll plan the treat into her day and work backward to make her other meals fit.
‚†Ä
This helps in two ways:
‚†Ä
1. She's better able to manage her total calorie intake.
‚†Ä
2. Because she knows a treat is coming later in the day, it makes it a helluva lot easier to stay on track with her earlier meals.
‚†Ä
~
‚†Ä
The strategies in this post are just a few of many things that can help you fight cravings and stay on track.
‚†Ä
At the end of the day, what's going to help you the most is recognizing that a) cravings are 100% normal, and b) you are 100% in control of them.
‚†Ä
I'm not saying you won't struggle with them.
‚†Ä
In fact, I guarantee you'll give in to cravings from time to time.
‚†Ä
But those are opportunities to learn and develop strategies that help you better manage your cravings long-term.
‚†Ä
So yeah‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
Just like everything else in fitness, the secret to "beating" your cravings isn't anything special or profound.
‚†Ä
It comes down to patience, consistency, and a willingness to learn from your mistakes.
‚†Ä
Big surprise, aye? ;)
‚†Ä
Again, these are just a few of many things you can do to fight cravings. If there's something you've done that's helped you, I'd love for you to share it below.
‚†Ä
Collectively, we can make a bigger ‚Äòn‚Äô better difference üí™
‚Äî

It‚Äôs that time of the year again.
‚†Ä
When people start to slow down and quietly drift away from their weight loss goals.
‚†Ä
It‚Äôs getting colder, it‚Äôs getting dark earlier, and considering all of the holiday celebrations, it‚Äôs getting harder to stay on track.
‚†Ä
Gyms owners & trainers capitalize on this too.
‚†Ä

‚†Ä

‚†Ä
But there are downsides too.
‚†Ä
One being that many of the ads, offers, and discounts you‚Äôll be seeing will instill unrealistic expectations for what‚Äôs possible.
‚†Ä
This is the fundamental problem with the fitness industry.
‚†Ä
Your desire to lose fat & look better naked gets exploited by companies promising ridiculously fast weight loss & results in just a few short months.
‚†Ä
Then they‚Äôll discount their programs & services to take advantage of your emotional high.
‚†Ä
Again, this isn‚Äôt always bad.
‚†Ä
Especially if you have the right mindset going in.
‚†Ä
Truth is, losing weight almost always happens a bit slower than you expect‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
[And that‚Äôs without considering the time it takes to build habits for maintaining your success.]
‚†Ä
If you aren‚Äôt making this journey enjoyable‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
Or at least maintainable‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
Then you‚Äôre setting yourself up for failure.

Losing weight & getting leaner for life comes down to two simple things:
‚†Ä
Blinders & Patience.

Blinders üèá: this is about YOUR success. Stop setting unrealistic goals, and stop comparing yourself to others.
‚†Ä
Patience‚è≥: YOUR success is going to take longer than you probably want, but that‚Äôs okay. You have time, and you know it‚Äôll be worth it in the end.
‚†Ä
Blinders & Patience ‚Äî make this your guiding phrase moving forward, and you will finally have the success you‚Äôve been wanting.

There‚Äôs no better real-life example of ‚Äúmissing the forest from the trees‚Äù than healthy eating.
‚†Ä
Everyone‚Äôs got their own opinion on what diet practices are optimal for fat loss, performance, and overall health.
‚†Ä
I have my own opinions too.
‚†Ä
And we could get into the weeds of nutrition if we wanted to‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
But why would we?
‚†Ä
Arguing super-duper specific differences in views won‚Äôt help you, me, or anyone else wanting to get lean, healthy, and happy.
‚†Ä
‚ÄúThere‚Äôs more to being healthy than eating healthy.‚Äù
‚†Ä
What I mean is this‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
WHAT you eat is important.
‚†Ä
But equally important is HOW YOU THINK about what you eat.
‚†Ä
[I‚Äôd even argue it‚Äôs more important]
‚†Ä
You could eliminate & restrict all ‚Äúbad‚Äù foods from your diet and only eat foods you deem as being ‚Äúgood.‚Äù
‚†Ä
But what does that do for your mental well-being?
‚†Ä
Does it create peace? Or does all of that restriction cause unnecessary stress in your day to day life.
‚†Ä
Does it empower you? Or does it isolate you from everyone and everything around you.
‚†Ä
Does it make you happy? Or does it keep you from enjoying other aspects of your life.
‚†Ä
~
‚†Ä
I‚Äôm not here to argue against the importance of eating healthy.
‚†Ä
Most of the time, you should be eating whole, nutrient-dense foods.
‚†Ä
Most of the time, you should be staying away from large quantities of highly-processed junk foods‚Ä¶
‚†Ä
But if you‚Äôre at your little nephew‚Äôs birthday party and he brings you a slice of cake, eat the freaking cake.
‚†Ä
If you‚Äôre on a date with your significant other at a fancy-pants restaurant, eat what the chef recommends.
‚†Ä
BEING healthy is about so much more than EATING healthy 100% of the time.
